<div class="read-content" align="center">
        <!-- Paste your full post here as paragraphs -->
        
<p>Letting go isn’t easy.<br>
Not because we don’t know how to release,<br>
but because what we’re letting go of once felt true.</p>

<p>Sometimes the hardest part is realizing<br>
that what we believed in<br>
was shaped by hope, not reality.<br>
That we didn’t imagine everything —<br>
we simply wanted to see the best,<br>
and held onto the parts that felt safe, promising, alive.</p>

<p>It hurts when the picture you carried<br>
slowly reveals its missing pieces.<br>
When what you trusted<br>
doesn’t reach back.<br>
When what you thought was mutual<br>
was only held on one side.</p>

<p>And still… listen.<br>
When things feel off, they usually are.<br>
Everything that chooses you<br>
doesn’t always mean it’s meant for you.<br>
The quiet knowing doesn’t arrive loudly —<br>
it waits patiently for your attention.</p>

<p>Letting go, then, isn’t about forgetting.<br>
It’s about loosening your grip on what never fully chose you.<br>
It’s about accepting that love, meaning, or belonging<br>
cannot be sustained by intention alone.</p>

<p>So if it feels heavy,<br>
if your hands ache from holding on too long,<br>
know this:<br>
you’re not weak for struggling to release.<br>
You were simply sincere in what you gave.</p>

<p>And with time, softly,<br>
you’ll learn that letting go<br>
isn’t the loss of what was imagined —<br>
it’s the return to what is true.</p>
</div>

